  "eprint": {
    "title": "Attacking Zcash For Fun And Profit",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Duke Leto",
        "email": "jaleto@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "The Hush Developers",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "This paper will outline, for the first time, exactly how the ITM Attack (a linkability attack against\nshielded transactions) works against Zcash Protocol and how Hush is the first cryptocoin with a defensive mitigation against it, called ”Sietch ”. Sietch is already running live in production and undergoing\nrounds of improvement from expert feedback. This is not an academic paper about pipedreams. It\ndescribes production code and networks.\nWe begin with a literature review of all known metadata attack methods that can be used against\nZcash Protocol blockchains. This includes their estimated attack costs and threat model. This paper\nthen describes the ”ITM Attack” which is a specific instance of a new class of metadata attacks against\nblockchains which the author describes as Metaverse Metadata Attacks .\nThe paper then explains Sietch in detail, which was a response to these new attacks. We hope this\nnew knowledge and theory helps cryptocoins increase their defenses against very well-funded adversaries including nation states and chain analysis companies.\nA few other new privacy issues and metadata attacks against Zcash Protocol coins will also be enumerated for the first time publicly. The ideas in this paper apply to all cryptocoins which utilize transaction graphs, which is to say just about all known coins. Specifically, the Metaverse Metadata class of\nattacks is applicable to all Bitcoin source code forks (including Dash, Verge, Zerocoin and their forks),\nCryptoNote Protocol coins (Monero and friends) and MimbleWimble Protocol (Grin, Beam, etc) coins\nbut these will not be addressed here other than a high-level description of how to apply these methods\nto those chains.\n\nIn privacy zdust we trust.\nIf dust can attack us, dust can protect us.\n– Sietch Mottos",
    "keywords": [
      "anonymity",
      "information hiding",
      "zero knowledge"
    ],
